{"action": "input", "code": "def find_square(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Finds a square of 4 grids of the same color in the center 6x6 grid of the input.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (10, 10) representing the input grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of 4 tuples, each containing the row and column indices of a grid in the square.\n    \"\"\"\n    center = input_grid[2:8, 2:8]\n    for i in range(6):\n        for j in range(6):\n            color = center[i, j]\n            if i + 1 < 6 and j + 1 < 6 and (center[i + 1, j] == color) and (center[i, j + 1] == color) and (center[i + 1, j + 1] == color):\n                return ((i + 2, j + 2), (i + 3, j + 2), (i + 2, j + 3), (i + 3, j + 3))\n    return ((0, 0), (0, 0), (0, 0), (0, 0))\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    square = find_square(input_grid)\n    output = fill_symmetric_parts(input_grid, square)\n    return output\ndef fill_symmetric_parts(input_grid: np.ndarray, square: Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Fills in the symmetric parts of the input grid based on the given square.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (10, 10) representing the input grid.\n    square: A tuple of 4 tuples, each containing the row and column indices of a grid in the square.\n\n    Returns:\n    A numpy array of shape (10, 10) representing the output grid with symmetric parts filled in.\n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    for i in range(4):\n        x1, y1 = square[i]\n        for j in range(i + 1, 4):\n            x2, y2 = square[j]\n            if x1 == x2 or y1 == y2:\n                continue\n            if output_grid[x1, y1] == maroon:\n                output_grid[x2, y2] = output_grid[x1, y1]\n                output_grid[x2, 9 - y2] = output_grid[x1, y1]\n                output_grid[9 - x2, y2] = output_grid[x1, y1]\n                output_grid[9 - x2, 9 - y2] = output_grid[x1, y1]\n            elif output_grid[x2, y2] == maroon:\n                output_grid[x1, y1] = output_grid[x2, y2]\n                output_grid[x1, 9 - y1] = output_grid[x2, y2]\n                output_grid[9 - x1, y1] = output_grid[x2, y2]\n                output_grid[9 - x1, 9 - y1] = output_grid[x2, y2]\n    return output_grid", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    square = `search in the 6*6 center of the input,find a square of 4 grids of the same color. return the positions of the 4 grids `(input_grid)\n    output = `each grid of the square and each corner of the input can make up 4 rectangles (4 parts of the input). Those parts are symmetric. If a part is shaded by a maroon coloerd shape, flip other part to fill in the shape and make the part symmetric. `(input_grid, square)\n    return output", "gpt_code": "def find_square(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Finds a square of 4 grids of the same color in the center 6x6 grid of the input.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (10, 10) representing the input grid.\n\n    Returns:\n    A tuple of 4 tuples, each containing the row and column indices of a grid in the square.\n    \"\"\"\n    center = input_grid[2:8, 2:8]\n    for i in range(6):\n        for j in range(6):\n            color = center[i, j]\n            if i + 1 < 6 and j + 1 < 6 and (center[i + 1, j] == color) and (center[i, j + 1] == color) and (center[i + 1, j + 1] == color):\n                return ((i + 2, j + 2), (i + 3, j + 2), (i + 2, j + 3), (i + 3, j + 3))\n    return ((0, 0), (0, 0), (0, 0), (0, 0))\ndef fill_symmetric_parts(input_grid: np.ndarray, square: Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]]) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Fills in the symmetric parts of the input grid based on the given square.\n\n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array of shape (10, 10) representing the input grid.\n    square: A tuple of 4 tuples, each containing the row and column indices of a grid in the square.\n\n    Returns:\n    A numpy array of shape (10, 10) representing the output grid with symmetric parts filled in.\n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    for i in range(4):\n        x1, y1 = square[i]\n        for j in range(i + 1, 4):\n            x2, y2 = square[j]\n            if x1 == x2 or y1 == y2:\n                continue\n            if output_grid[x1, y1] == maroon:\n                output_grid[x2, y2] = output_grid[x1, y1]\n                output_grid[x2, 9 - y2] = output_grid[x1, y1]\n                output_grid[9 - x2, y2] = output_grid[x1, y1]\n                output_grid[9 - x2, 9 - y2] = output_grid[x1, y1]\n            elif output_grid[x2, y2] == maroon:\n                output_grid[x1, y1] = output_grid[x2, y2]\n                output_grid[x1, 9 - y1] = output_grid[x2, y2]\n                output_grid[9 - x1, y1] = output_grid[x2, y2]\n                output_grid[9 - x1, 9 - y1] = output_grid[x2, y2]\n    return output_grid", "holes": {"find_square": "search in the 6*6 center of the input,find a square of 4 grids of the same color. return the positions of the 4 grids ", "fill_symmetric_parts": "each grid of the square and each corner of the input can make up 4 rectangles (4 parts of the input). Those parts are symmetric. If a part is shaded by a maroon coloerd shape, flip other part to fill in the shape and make the part symmetric. "}}
